sometimes we need to bookmark certain points int he history,
label a commit as specific one, like a commit that represent a version.
or a commit that introduce some important feature.


git tag v1.0             //create tag on current commit (last commit)

git tag v1.0 5a66b8fd    //create tag on 5a66b8fd


Note: we can see tag on log:      dd889bd (HEAD -> main) tags
                                  18e1662 (tag: v1.0) blame         //this commit has tag
                                  c3ca9f3 shortlog
                                  0818300 binary search on commits
                                  a8f8f91 checkout a commit
                                  caea949 checkout a commit

Note: we can checkout (move HEAD) on commit
      by his tag!
      "git checkout v1.0"

Note: we can see all the tags we defined by
      "git tag"

LIGHTWEIGHT TAG
it just a pointer to a commit (just like a branch)
the v1.0 that we defined earlier was lightweight tag!

ANNOTATE TAG
it's another tag that is more than a pointer!
it's a complete object with a bunch of properties
like tagger name, emil, message,...
(it's separate object, not just a reference!)

git tag -a v1.1 -m "annotated tag!"     //-a create annotated tag (create an object)
                                        //not just a reference or pointer
                                        //it put tag on last commit

----------------------------------

git tag -n      //show tag messages

v1.0            blame               //it's the commit message
v1.1            annotated tag

Note: LIGHTWEIGHT tags is just a pointer, so he just show commit message!
      ANNOTATED tag is separate object, it has own message (we used -m)


----------------------------------

git show v1.1       //we can show a commit by his tag!

git tag -d v1.1     //delete tag!